---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How to Lower Your BMI: Evidence-Based Steps That Work"
  description="Learn how to lower your BMI safely and sustainably. Evidence-based guidance on calorie deficit, strength training, sleep, stress management, and realistic timelines for BMI reduction."
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6">

    <p class="text-sm font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-(--color-accent-deep)">How-to</p>
    <h1 class="font-display mt-2 text-4xl font-bold text-(--color-ink)">
      How to Lower Your BMI: Evidence-Based Steps That Work
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-(--color-body)">
      If your BMI is above 25 and you want to bring it down, here's what the research actually supports — no crash diets, no extreme programmes.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-4 text-xs text-(--color-mute)">Published: June 2026 · 7 min read</div>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-8 text-(--color-body) leading-relaxed">

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">How much can BMI change?</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          BMI drops by roughly <strong>1 unit per 3 kg (6.6 lb)</strong> of weight loss for an average-height
          adult. To move from overweight (BMI 27) to normal (BMI 24.9), a 170 cm person would need to
          lose approximately 6 kg (13 lb). A realistic, sustainable rate is 0.5–1 kg per week — so that's
          6–12 weeks of consistent effort.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">1. Create a moderate calorie deficit</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Losing 0.5 kg per week requires burning roughly 500 calories more than you consume per day.
          This doesn't require extreme restriction — for most people it's the difference between
          eating 1,800 kcal vs 2,300 kcal.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 text-sm">
          <li>Use a food tracking app for 2–4 weeks to establish your baseline</li>
          <li>Prioritise protein (1.2–1.6 g/kg body weight) — it preserves muscle and increases satiety</li>
          <li>Reduce ultra-processed foods and liquid calories (alcohol, sugary drinks) first</li>
          <li>Avoid deficits over 1,000 kcal/day — muscle loss, nutrient deficiencies, and rebound risk increase significantly</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">2. Add resistance training</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Cardio burns calories during exercise; strength training raises your resting metabolic rate
          for 24–48 hours afterward. More importantly, building muscle means more of your weight loss
          comes from fat, not lean tissue.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          2–3 sessions of full-body resistance training per week — bodyweight, free weights, or machines
          — is sufficient for most people. Progressive overload (gradually increasing resistance) drives
          continued adaptation.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">3. Increase daily movement (NEAT)</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Non-Exercise Activity Thermogenesis (NEAT) — the calories you burn walking, fidgeting, standing,
          doing chores — accounts for 200–800 kcal/day in most people. It's often more impactful than
          structured exercise.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 text-sm">
          <li>Aim for 8,000–10,000 steps per day</li>
          <li>Take stairs, walk to nearby destinations, stand during calls</li>
          <li>A standing desk can add 50–150 kcal/day burned</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">4. Prioritise sleep</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Sleeping under 6 hours per night increases ghrelin (hunger hormone) and decreases leptin
          (satiety hormone), making it significantly harder to maintain a calorie deficit. Short sleepers
          eat an average of 300–400 extra calories per day compared to those sleeping 7–9 hours.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          If you're struggling to lose weight despite a good diet, sleep is often the missing variable.
          Target 7–9 hours of consistent sleep, with a regular bedtime.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">5. Manage chronic stress</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Cortisol (the stress hormone) promotes visceral fat storage and increases appetite for
          calorie-dense foods. Chronic work stress, poor sleep, and emotional strain can make weight
          loss significantly harder even when calorie intake is controlled.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 text-sm">
          <li>Regular exercise itself is one of the best stress reducers</li>
          <li>Mindfulness and breathing techniques reduce cortisol</li>
          <li>Addressing the source of stress (workload, relationships) is more effective long-term than coping techniques alone</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Realistic timelines</h2>
        <div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline)">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
            <thead class="bg-(--color-canvas)">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Goal</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Weight to lose</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Realistic time</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-(--color-hairline)">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">BMI 27 → 24.9 (overweight to normal)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">~6 kg</td><td class="px-4 py-3">6–12 weeks</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">BMI 30 → 24.9 (obese to normal)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">~15 kg</td><td class="px-4 py-3">4–7 months</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">BMI 35 → 24.9 (Class II → normal)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">~30 kg</td><td class="px-4 py-3">8–16 months</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-(--color-mute)">Estimates assume 0.5–1 kg/week loss rate for a 170 cm person. Individual results vary.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">What doesn't work</h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-sm">
          <li><strong>Crash diets under 800 kcal/day</strong> — cause rapid muscle loss, nutrient deficiencies, and almost always lead to rebound weight gain</li>
          <li><strong>Spot reduction</strong> — you cannot choose where your body loses fat; it's determined genetically</li>
          <li><strong>Exercise without diet changes</strong> — exercise alone rarely produces more than 0.1–0.2 kg/week loss; appetite often compensates</li>
          <li><strong>Supplements claiming to "burn fat"</strong> — none have clinically meaningful effects without diet and exercise</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline) bg-(--color-canvas) p-5">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Track your starting point</p>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-(--color-body)">Calculate your BMI now and save your baseline — our calculator stores your last 5 results locally.</p>
      <a href="/" class="mt-3 inline-block rounded-xl bg-(--color-accent) px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-white hover:opacity-90 transition">
        Open BMI Calculator →
      </a>
    </div>

    <p class="mt-8 text-xs text-(--color-mute)">
      This article is for educational purposes only. Always consult a qualified healthcare provider before starting a weight management programme.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4 text-sm">
      <a href="/blog" class="text-(--color-link) hover:underline">← All articles</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
